OriginalAxioms:
:Color rdfs:comment The Class of Attributes relating to the color of Objects.
    
      Color is an AttributeType, and the actual values of Color are
         instances of ColorAttributeType, which are subtypes of ColorAttribute.
         
       The WordNet color sense 1 is ambiguous between the general type this type and
         the individual attributes:
         1. 51 color, colour, coloring, colouring - a visual attribute of things 
         vvthat results from the light they emit or transmit or reflect;
         a white color is made up of many different wavelengths of light

:CustomarySystemOfLinks rdfs:comment A specialization of #$SpatialThing-Localized.
            Each instance of #$CustomarySystemOfLinks is a customary or
            conventional network system consisting of interconnected
            links instances of #$Path-Customary and nodes of obvious
            types, where the elements of the system i.e., the points,
            nodes, and links of the system can be assumed without
            specifying them as sets note that this is in contrast to
            instances of #$PathSystem, in which the sets of point,
            nodes, links, and loops if any have to be specified for
            the system.  Instances of #$CustomarySystemOfLinks include
            pipe systems, road systems, vascular systems, wiring
            systems, and mechanical linkages.  The links of any
            #$CustomarySystemOfLinks are assumed to share certain
            characteristics.  For example, in a road system, pipes are
            not links, nor are streetlights, road paint, or other
            non-roadways; only the roadways forming the road system are
            links in that system.  Moreover, what constitutes a
            #$JunctionOfPaths q.v. or #$pathTerminus q.v. in the
            system should be obvious from the system type.   The links
            are related to the assumed system by
            #$linksOfCustomarySystem q.v..

:Pincushion rdfs:comment A small, soft, stuffed bag Artifact used to support straight pins,
           often during clothing manufacture.
          
          NOTE: this is not a subtpe of Cushion as in WordNet which in 
             CSMO is used to support people.
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of pincushion in Wordnet:
              1. pincushion - a small stiff cushion into which pins are stuck ready for use

:AppearingEvent rdfs:comment An AppearingEvent is an Event in which some PhysicalObject which was not
    previously visible to an observer becomes visible to that observer.  The
    AppearingEvent can be caused by motion of the object which appears, or by
    motion of some object between the observer and the object that appears,
    or by motion of the observer who gains a perspective that allows viewing the
    object.  It can also occur by some other change in the object, as by increase
    in size, or increase in luminosity, or increase in ambient light.  It can also
    occur by the observer using some device that allows an otherwise imperceptible
    thing to become visible - e.g. a microscope, a telescope, or night-vision goggles.
    This does not include the sense of appears to be seems like - for that
    sense use AppearingToBe.
     
     Corresponds to verb sense 2 of appear in WordNet:
       2. 102 appear - come into sight or view; He suddenly appeared at the wedding;
         A new star appeared on the horizon

:Polymer rdfs:comment A Polymer is a substance composed predominantly of large
      molecules that themselves contain many units of similar type linked 
      together by chemical bonds.  Plastics and biopolymers
      are the most important polymers.  A Polymer may be Organic or Inorganic.
      
      Each molecule has a Sequence of monomer units which usually have some
        characteristics in common, and often are identical or small variants on 
        some moleculular structure.
      
      Corresponds to noun sense 1 of polymer in WordNet:
        1. polymer - a naturally occurring or synthetic compound consisting
         of large molecules made up of a linked series of repeated simple monomers

:Pinch rdfs:comment A minor and usually inconsequential injury to the skin,
            which is caused by a squeezing or pinching force applied to 
            the skin, but not including a piercing of the skin.  
            A small Pinch may not cause any inflammatory response, and the 
              pain may disappear  rapidly, but a stronger Pinch may cause a bruise.
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 2 of pinch in WordNet:
              2. pinch - an injury resulting from getting some body part squeezed

:eventually rdfs:comment The adverb eventually is similar tofinally
      in expressing the notion of something happening after some 
      long and unusual or unnecessary lapse of time.  As used in COSMO
      finally is used to describe *past* events that took place, whereas
      eventually is used to refer to *future* events that are expected to occur
      sooner or later.
      
         Corresponds to adverb sense 1 of eventually in WordNet:
            . 19 eventually, yet, sooner or later, in time, one of these days - 
              within an indefinite time or at an unspecified future time; 
              he will understand eventually; he longed for the flowers that were 
              yet to show themselves; sooner or later you will have to face the facts; 
              in time they came to accept the harsh reality
     .

:hadHonoree rdfs:comment hadHonoree relates any of various Events to the
        to some Agent person, group, Organization that is being
        singled out for esteem on a particular occasion.
        Occasions are for example, parties to honor a 
        person e.g. birthday partees, award ceremonies, 
        selection of person of the year events, inaugurations, etc.
        Usually a Person, but sometimes an Organization or Group of People.

:RegularlyScheduled rdfs:comment RegularlyScheduled is a FrequencyAttributeValue 
       for Events that occur at fixed time intervals because they 
       have been planned in advance to occur at those times;
       this is commonly used for meetings and other social events,
       but can also be used for Actions such as routine 
       maintenance procedures. If this attribute is applied and
       the frequency is also known, the actual value of
       the Frequency should be specified, using the
       hasFrequency relation
       @ToDo: The use of specific time-interval
       adjectives specifying specific time intervals such as
       daily, monthly biannual might be thought of as subtypes
       of this type, but being quantitative are represented as
       instances of Frequency.  IT is possible to create
       subtypes of this type such as ScheduledDaily that
       differ from the quantitative measure daily, but
       as of rev833 those subtypes have not been defined.
       The word usualcan refer to regularly scheduled activities,
       as in we held our usual group meeting in room 302 today
      
      
      NOTE: Conventional may be assigned
      to some activity to express the notion that it occurs at some
      fixed time of day, or day of the month; such an activity may also
      be RegularlyScheduled, and will then have both attributes:
      Conventional and RegularlyScheduled.  The distinction is 
      that some activity may be RegularlyScheduled in the sense of 
      occuring every week, but may not be held on the same day of every
      week or at the same time of day; conversely, an activity may
      be typically held at a perticular time of day, but may not occur
      at fixed time intervals.  More specific subtypes of
      Conventional may be needed to express such nuances.  Thus 
      regular bedtime and usual bedtime and normal bedtime all
      have the attribute Conventional.  For activities that occur
      at a particular time of day, day of the week and also recur
      at fixed time intervals, use OccurringAtaFixedTime.
      

      Corresponds to adjective sense 5  of regular and
        part of sense 1 of usual in WordNet:
        5. 2 regular - regularly scheduled for fixed times;
            at a regular meeting of the PTA; regular bus departures
        WN usual:
           1. 29 usual - occurring or encountered or experienced or observed 
            frequently or in accordance with regular practice or procedure;
            grew the usual vegetables; the usual summer heat; came at the usual time;
            the childs usual bedtime

:AnonymousAuthor rdfs:comment AnonymousAuthor is the Type representing all
         AuthorOfRecords that are listed officially as Anonymous.
         Instances of this Type can be used as object of the wasAuthoredBy
         relation.  Each case where an author is listed as Anonymous should be
         recorded as a separate instance of AnonymousAuthor so as to
         avoid the inference that all things written by Anonymous were written
         by the same  person.  One could use Anonymous001, Anonymous2685, etc.
         as the anonymous authors of specific works, or, to make it easier to
         recognize that anonymous individual directly from the name, one could use e,g,
         Anonymous_PrimaryColors to indicate the work that the anonymous
         authored.  If it is known in fact that the same anonymous author authored more than one work,
         the same instance of AnonymousAuthor can be used as the
         filler for wasAuthoredBy.
         
            To specify that some author was anonymous without creating a new
            instance of Author, use UnidentifiedAuthor, which has the
            attribute Unidentified and that will signal the reasoner to not try
            to equate that instance with any other.

:CrossingSomething rdfs:comment Any Event in which some object crosses
           over or trough some object or region.  This differs
           from Translation-LocationChange only in that there
           is something specific that is crossed.
           
           Corresponds to verb sense 1 of cross in WordNet:
             1. 48 traverse, track, cover, cross, pass over, get over, get across, 
                cut through, cut across - travel across or pass over; 
                The caravan covered almost 100 miles each day

:Full rdfs:comment To be Full is for a container-like thing to contain as 
           much as it is capable of holding.  This can be applied to 
           abstract objects as well as PhysicalObjects.  Full when applied to containers 
           specifies  that the volume of its contents is equal to the capacity,
           and no more contents can be added.
           
           Corresponds to adjective sense 1 of full and part of semse 1 of filled in WordNet:
           1. 42 full - containing as much or as many as is possible or normal;
              a full glass; a sky full of stars; a full life;
              the auditorium was full to overflowing.
            WN adj filled:
              1. 27 filled - usually followed by with or used as a combining form 
                generously supplied with; theirs was a house filled with laughter;
                a large hall filled with rows of desks; fog-filled air

:Steak rdfs:comment A Steak is a MeatObject  consisting of cooked meat, usually referring
       to beef, but also to other types of meat.
    
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of steak in Wordnet:
           1. 2 steak - a slice of meat cut from the fleshy part of an animal or large fish

:FeedingAnOrganism rdfs:comment A collection of events.  In an instance of
            #$FeedingEvent, an agent intentionally supplies food to an
            organism.  In this sense, feeding is not the same as eating.
            Rather, a feeding event is a prelude to some #$EatingEvent
            which is expected to follow the feeding.  The food may be
            placed into the intended recipients mouth or where it
            can be reached easily by the recipient.   Feeding may be
            done by one agent for another, but an organism may also feed
            itself.  Feeding is part of the care of captive animals, as
            well as of caring by a parent for its offspring in most species.
            
            Corresponds to verb senses 1 and 2  of feed in WordNet,
               conflating both the transitive and ditransitive senses,
               which @ToDo should be distinguished.
             1. 47 feed - provide as food; Feed the guests the nuts
             2. 15 feed, give - give food to; Feed the starving children in India;
               dont give the child this tough meat

:Paring rdfs:comment A part piece of the surface of a fruit or vegetable, of
           undefined thickness,  of usually FruitRind or FruitSkin or
            skin of a potato that has been removed from the whole by a
           peeling or paring process with or without a knife.
            Such a piece  is relatively thin compared to the
            original fruit.  
            
            @ToDo: could this or  parent be applied to non-plant objects?  For wood, would
               be a shaving
            
             Corresponds to sense 10 of peel in RHW:
              peel  10. the skin or rind of a fruit, vegetable, etc.            
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 2 of paring in WordNet:
	      2. paring - usually plural a part of a fruit or vegetable that
	         is pared or cut off; especially the skin or peel;
	         she could peel an apple with a single long paring

:ComputerNetworkPathSystem rdfs:comment A ComputerNetworkPathSystem is the abstract system of paths
      not the physical connections that connect a computer network.

:hasLimitedSituation rdfs:comment hasLimitedSituation relates a Limit to the specific
       SituationProcessEventOrState, in which the limit exists.
       
         Add Region??

:Purpose rdfs:comment A Purpose is a special subtype of Goal for which
          an agent requires some Resource.  When an agent requires a resource, it is to
          achieve some Purpose.  This use of the term Purpose is more specialized than
          the common uses, which often overlap with Goal.
          
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of purpose in Wordnet:
               1. 75 purpose, intent, intention, aim, design - an anticipated outcome
                that is intended or that guides your planned actions; his intent was to 
                provide a new translation; good intentions are not enough; it was created 
                with the conscious aim of answering immediate needs; he made no secret of his designs

:UnpleasantPerson rdfs:comment Any Person who behaves in a disagreeable manner- a Role that may not be
      a permanent trait.
       
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of unpleasant person in WordNet:
          1. unpleasant person, disagreeable person - a person who is not pleasant or agreeable

:SensoryCapabilityType rdfs:comment Each instance of metaclass SensoryCapabilityType is some subtype of
      SensoryAbility such as hearing, touch, sight, etc.  This applies to both
      organisms and artifacts with perceptual capability.
      .

:Hydrocolloid rdfs:comment Each subtype of  Hydrocolloid is an instance of SubstanceType that can
            form a gel when mixed with water.
            
            This is included mostly to provide a parent for Jell-O
           
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of hydrocolloid in WordNet;
              1. hydrocolloid - a substance that forms a gel with water

:Japan rdfs:comment 
    
     Corresponds to noun sense 1 of Japan capitalized in WordNet:
        1. 6 Japan, Japanese Islands, Japanese Archipelago - a string of
           more than 3,000 islands east of Asia extending 1,300 miles between
           the Sea of Japan and the western Pacific Ocean
:TwoTerminalElectricalDevice rdfs:comment electrical devices with two terminals

:Comb rdfs:comment A Device that fits in the hand, generally flat but
          containing multiple narrow parallel tines narrowly
          spaced, used mostly to straighten tangled hair or fur.
          
          Includes but is broader than CYC CombForHair
          CYC:  The collection of all combs for combing hair
          
          Corresponds to noun sense 1 of comb in WordNet:
          1. 3 comb - a flat device with narrow pointed teeth on one edge;
            disentangles or arranges hair

:ConnectiveTissue rdfs:comment COSMO: this is a piece of connective tissue,
         an object, not a substance.
         
         Cyc: The #$Collection of all instances of
            #$ConnectiveTissue.  Subsets of this collection include
            #$Aponeurosis, #$Tendon, Fascia, Collagen, etc.
:ActionGroup rdfs:comment A Group consisting exclusively of Actions.

:ProcessionEvent rdfs:comment A SocialGathering in which some GroupOfPeople possibly in vehicles
          form a Procession and move in an orderly manner, usually by
          forming a line which may have more than one person in 
          a row and moving along the same route.  Vehicles may
          be ridden during a procession, but this is a SocialGathering, and
          the ProcessionEvent cannot have a commercial purpose.  Some element
          of ceremony or formality is required to make something a ProcessionEvent
          but the criteria are broad.  However, the movement of a
          military column is *not* a Procession, nor is a group of
          people moving along the same route in a competition such as a
          race.  A ProcessionEvent can
          be a funeral procession, a procession of students at a
          graduation, or even a parade; a ProcessionEvent need not be 
          solemn.  A ProcessionEvent usually takes place on a surface-
          on land or sea an awesome procession of tall ships up the river,
          but a Procession of airplanes is a possible instance.
          
           The size, purpose, and location of a Procession can be from very small
          to very large.
          
           A scripted Procession performed for the purpose of displaying or commemorating
                or celebrating something, in anticipation of being seen by a group of spectators, is
                categorized as the subtype ParadeEvent
          
          Corresponds to part of noun sense 2 of procession in WordNet;
            only the movement of people is included in this type:
            2. procession - the group action of a collection of people or animals 
             or vehicles moving ahead in more or less regular formation;
             processions were forbidden

:IBTRecoding rdfs:comment A specialization of #$IBTGeneration-Replication.
            Each instance of #$IBTRecoding is an event which generates a
            new information-bearing thing i.e., an instance of
            #$InformationBearingThing by taking information from a
            source information-bearing thing see #$informationOrigin,
            encoding it a new way, and incorporating it into a new
            information-bearing thing see #$ibtGenerated.  Instances
            of #$IBTRecoding may be done either by agents e.g., people
            or by non-agents e.g., record players, or computers running
            translation software.  Recoding the content of a
            pre-existing information-bearing thing presupposes some
            instance of accessing it i.e., of #$AccessingAnIBT.

:Revenue rdfs:comment Revenue is the total of PaymentAmounts that are received in some
      particular time interval by some LegalAgent, not corrected for any
      costs incurred in obtaining the payments.  For a business this would be the
      gross receipts. Accontants my calculate the Revenue in different ways 
      depending on the way oney is paid or promised.  This includes
      revenues for governmental organizations as well as private organizations and individual,
      and also includes the sum of donations to charitabl organizations, not just
      taxes or sales.

      For individuals, use Income.
      
       Includes noun senses 1 and 2 of revenue in WordNet:
            1. 5 gross, revenue, receipts - the entire amount of income before any deductions are made
            2. tax income, taxation, tax revenue, revenue - government income due to taxation

:LigandType rdfs:comment A specialization of
            #$ChemicalCompoundTypeByChemicalSpecies. Instances of
            #$LigandType are collections whose instances are substances
            capable of surrounding and bonding to a central metal ion,
            forming a metal complex or simply complex. In forming a
            complex, the ligands are considered to coordinate to the metal.

:InterAgentSituation-TwoAgent rdfs:comment The class of reified relationships between two
            agents.  Such relationships exist in time and change over
            time, so #$SomethingExisting is an allgenls.

:StatusGoal rdfs:comment COSMO note: in COSMO a mental object.
        
         Cyc: This attribute characterizes goals which are
            concerned with an agents status in or with another
            agent or group of agents.  The kinds of status
            at issue here include an agents level of prestige,
            power, and influence, and position within an organization.
            Correspondingly, the kinds of agents or groups in which one
            can have a status includes organizations,
            geographical regions, professional groups, and peer groups.
            Examples of goals which may be qualified with #$StatusGoal
            include a countrys goal of broadening its sphere of
            influence, and an academics goal of being influential
            in his field of study.

:Beast rdfs:comment Another term for NonHumanAnimal. Taint a fit
          night out for man nor beast.

:Woman rdfs:comment An adult female human.
          CYC has AdultFemalHuman - probably the same.
          
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of woman in WordNet:
          1. 480 woman, adult female - - an adult female person as opposed to a man;
          the woman kept house while the man hunted

:GreaterThanNumber rdfs:comment Any Number in some range that is greater than the specified
        value, related by the hasLowerLimit relation.  The range of
        permitted values does not include the limit.  The implementation
        will have to interpret these numbers in whatever manner less-than
        and greater-than numbers are interpreted.

:DomesticPartner rdfs:comment DomesticPartner is The Role of a Companion
         who lives together in a loving and often intimate relationship 
         with a Person as a living unit, whether
         married or unmarried, homosexual or heterosexual.
         Tax laws, employment conditions, and some states may formally
          recognize this relationship.
          
          Merely sharing a living space does not qualify as being a DomesticPartner.
                
        Corresponds to sense 1 of domestic partner in WordNet:
          1. domestic partner, significant other, spousal equivalent, spouse equivalent -
            a person not necessarily a spouse with whom you cohabit and share a 
            long-term sexual relationship
:Burning rdfs:comment The common term for Combustion.

:isGreaterThanOrEqualTo rdfs:comment A #$NumericComparisonPredicate q.v. that is a
             generalization of the mathematical greater-than-or equal-to
             =; relation to #$ScalarIntervals
             q.v. of all sorts, including quantitative intervals see
             #$NumericInterval and #$Quantity as well as point values
             see #$ScalarPointValue.  #$greaterThanOrEqualTo
             VALUE1 VALUE2 means that
             VALUE1 is greater than or equal to VALUE2 with respect to
             some scale that they are both on.  More precisely, there is some
             #$TotallyOrderedScalarIntervalType SCALE;
             that both VALUE1; and
             VALUE2; are instances of and either i
             SCALE; is a specialization of
             #$NumericInterval e.g. #$RealNumber and the minimum see
             #$minQuantValue of VALUE1; is greater
             than or equal to the maximum see #$maxQuantValue of
             VALUE2;, ii
             #$followingValueOnScale VALUE2 VALUE1
             SCALE; holds, or iii #$equals VALUE1
             VALUE2; holds.    See also #$greaterThan and #$lessThanOrEqualTo.

:RandomChoice rdfs:comment A RandomChoice is something object, event chosen
           in a ChoosingAtRandom event.

:Clothing-Top rdfs:comment #$Clothing-Top is a specialization of #$Garment.
            Each instance of #$Clothing-Top is a #$Garment that extends
            from the shoulders to the #$Waist or #$Hips.
            #$Clothing-Tops are outerwear, in the sense that in modern
            western culture someone wearing a #$Clothing-Top with
            trousers, shorts, or a skirt and shoes is considered #$FullyClothed.

:Senior rdfs:comment Senior is a ComparativeAttribute that attributes to
           some Person  a higher rank or status than some other persons due to longer time that the 
           Person occupied a position.
           
              Corresponds to adjective sense 1 of senior in WordNet:
                1. 3 senior - older; higher in rank; longer in length
                of tenure or service; senior officer

:Nightingale rdfs:comment 
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of nightingale in WordNet:
             1. 2 nightingale, Luscinia megarhynchos - European songbird 
                noted for its melodious nocturnal song
:OccupationalRole rdfs:comment The SUMO approximate equivalent of PersonWithOccupation.

:hasDimensionality rdfs:comment hasDimensionalityNumber relates an Object or region to the 
       number of othogonal dimensions that it occupies, expressed as
       a DimensionalityValue.  This relation is complementary to hasDimensionalityNumber,
       which allows one to use a simple datatype integer as the value of the relation.
       CardinalityValues Are QuantitativeAttributeValues having the dimension dimensional.
       A PhysicalObject would have its dimenionality specified in ESKIF,
       using this relation, thus:
             Every PhysicalObject hasDimensionality {3 dimensional}.

       
       For objects whose specification has dimensions that are non-orthogonal,
       the Dimensionality should be the number of orthogonal 
       dimensions to which the non-orthogonal dimensions can be reduced.
       PhysicalObjects will always be 3-dimensional.  they may have
       surfaces that are 2-Dimensional, edges that are 1-Dimensional, and
       representations that are 2D and also 2-1/2 dimensional.

:wasSupportedByAgent rdfs:comment Points from an instance of Assertion a proposition
         or LinguisticAssertion to an Agent who asserted its truth.  There may
         be many agents who assert the truth of some Assertion, and they need not be
         the same as the agent who created the assertion originally.
         
         Corresponds most closely to adjective sense 1 of according in WordNet:
           1. 4 according - followed by to as reported or stated by;
              "according to historians"

:GeographicMap rdfs:comment A Map of some region of the Earths surface,
          represented as an oblong region whose sides correspond
          to latitude lines and longitude lines.  A GeographicMap
          is therefore typically represented as oriented North
          at the top of the image.  As an AbstractImage, it can
          be physically represented at any size.  Therefore a
          scale is not an appropriate attribute.  For abstract
          Maps that are intended to be printed at some size, a subtype will
          be needed.  Physical maps are represented as 
          PhysicalMap, and those can have a scale.
          
          The area of each GeographicMap coincides with the area
          of some GeographicalRectangle. this is not yet formalized

:LoopedHandle rdfs:comment A LoopedHandle is a Handle that has a loop a LoopShaped end
          to make grasping more secure.  
          The handles on the end of each blade of a scissors is an example; likewise,
          the loop on the end of a sword, or on some shovels.  A Jug in COSMO
          is a Container that must have a LoopedHandle,

:hasAltitude rdfs:comment An instance-level relation that specifies the the Altitude above
      the sea level datum of the approximate centroid location of  an object or Region.
      For points, the location should be exact, within the error of 
      measurement.  The value of this relation is an AltitudeValue, consisting
      of a quantifier and unit of Length.

:TopSail rdfs:comment The topsail of a sailboat.
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of topsail in WordNet:
              1. topsail - a sail or either of a pair of sails immediately above 
              the lowermost sail of a mast and supported by a topmast

:AdoptingaFamilyMember rdfs:comment AdoptingaFamilyMember is a ServiceEvent in which
          some person or Family agrees to accept take in some Person, usually a
~~          child, to become a family member.
             This is an Offering in that it is an offering to provide support a seervice
              for the adopted Person as a member of the family.

               Corresponds to verb sense 5 of adopt in WordNet:
                 5. 2 adopt, take in - take into ones family; They adopted two children from Nicaragua
              WN noun adoption:
                2. adoption - a legal proceeding that creates a parent-child relation
                   between persons not related by blood; the adopted child is entitled 
                   to all privileges belonging to a natural child of the adoptive parents 
                   including the right to inherit

:OrganismPart rdfs:comment COSMO note: an object is considered as an OrganismPart
           even if it was severed from the Organism of which it was originally
           a part.  The distinction, when required, between in situ and
           separated parts is made by assigning attributes to the part.
        
        
            A specialization of both #$PhysicalPartOfObject
            and #$BiologicalLivingObject. Each instance of
            OrganismPart is an anatomical part of an organism.  This
            collection includes the gross anatomical parts and
            microscopic anatomical parts of every individual of every species.
            
            In SUMO, approximate equivalent is AnatomicalStructure
            SUMO: A collection of Cells and Tissues which 
	    are localized to a specific area of an Organism and which are not 
	    pathological. The instances of this Class range from gross structures 
            to small components of complex Organs.

:Fan-ElectricalAppliance rdfs:comment Electric Fan appliance usually used for cooling people.
        
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of electric fan in Wordnet:
              1. electric fan, blower - a fan run by an electric motor

:Offering rdfs:comment In Cyc called Offering-CommunicationAct:
          This is very broad, including offering an opinion, or something
          for sale, or to do something, or something to eat, or condolences.
          Essentially, to linguistically verbally or in writing  present
          something for acceptance or rejection to another person, group,
          or to the public.  A rejection would be aninstance of DecliningAnOffer.

          This would include the legal concept of an offer that can be acepted to 
            create a contract, but is broader,not requiring any reciprocal thing of value.
            
          If the Offering is an offer to give or lend something for an agents use, that would be
             a subtype of MakingSomethingAvailable, but not all Offering actions fit
             into that category.
             
          In some cases an Offering may be performed gesturally, and that is still
            considered as an AssertingEvent though it does not use verbal communication.
            For example, at a  cocktail hour a waiter may put a tray of hors doeuvres in front of
            one, consituting an offer of the food - this is an instance of assertion and declining to take 
            any object thus offered is an instance of this type DecliningAnOffer.            .
          
          This Action communicates a willingness to do something.
        
        Cyc: A specialization of #$CommunicationAct-Single.
            Each instance of #$Offering-CommunicationAct is a
            communication act in which somebody offers to do something,
            furnish something, or make something the case. See also the
            #$IllocutionaryForce associated with these actions, #$Offer.
            
            SUMO: The subclass of Committing in which a IntentionalAgent
            offers something Physical to another agent. Offerings may
            be unconditional in which case they are a promise 
            to effect a UnilateralGiving or conditional in which case 
            they are a promise to effect a Transaction of some sort.
            
            NOTE: SUMO mentions Physical things offered, but in
            COSMO the thing offered may also be Mental or as with intangible
            assets like rights, abstract.
            
         Includes senses 1 through 7 of offer in Wordnet;
            1. 95 offer - make available or accessible, provide or furnish; 
                The conference center offers a health spa; 
                The hotel offers private meeting rooms
	    2. 31 offer, proffer - present for acceptance or rejection;
	        She offered us all a cold drink
	    3. 12 volunteer, offer - agree freely; She volunteered to drive 
	        the old lady home; I offered to help with the dishes but the hostess would not hear of it
	    4. 4 offer - put forward for consideration; He offered his opinion
	    5. 3 offer, extend - offer verbally; extend my greetings; 
	        He offered his sympathy
	    6. 3 offer - make available for sale; The stores are offering

:isContainedIn rdfs:comment isContainedIn is the inverse of contains and
            expresses a very general notion of some physical entity or region being contained in some
            way in something else.  This does not apply to abstract entities - see
            isContainedInSymbolicObject.  Although this relation implies for physical objects that the 
            contained thing isLocatedAtOrOn the containing thing, this cannot be a 
            subproperty because substances are included in this relation, and location is not relevant in that case.
            
            This generic relation as applied to PhysicalObjects not to substances 
                      only specifies that the thing contained is somewhere either
              1 within the convex hull of the containing thing, or
              2 piled on or resting in an open-top container, being held in place by
                the force of gravity. Things that are contained
                in a container must move in synchronization with the container
                when the container is moved.  Thus a flower in a vase, that 
                extends above the top of the vase, isContainedIn the vase.
                
                NOTE: the case of something that is partly in an object,
                extending beyond the limits of the object, but held 
                to the object by some topological constraint is not
                included in this relation.  That relation would be subsumed
                by isConnectedTo.

                   abstract notion of contain texts containing other texts or ideas;
                   also, the range will satisfy the meaning of the word contents,
                   which is part of sense 1 of content in WordNet:  also expressed
                   by the preposition in, but requiring some verbal connector

       @ToDo: The use of specific time-interval
       adjectives specifying specific time intervals such as
       daily, monthly biannual might be thought of as subtypes
       of this type, but being quantitative are represented as
       instances of Frequency.  IT is possible to create
       subtypes of this type such as ScheduledDaily that
       differ from the quantitative measure daily, but
       as of rev833 those subtypes have not been defined.
       The word usualcan refer to regularly scheduled activities,
       as in we held our usual group meeting in room 302 today
      
      
      NOTE: Conventional may be assigned
      to some activity to express the notion that it occurs at some
      fixed time of day, or day of the month; such an activity may also
      be RegularlyScheduled, and will then have both attributes:
      Conventional and RegularlyScheduled.  The distinction is 
      that some activity may be RegularlyScheduled in the sense of 
      occuring every week, but may not be held on the same day of every
      week or at the same time of day; conversely, an activity may
      be typically held at a perticular time of day, but may not occur
      at fixed time intervals.  More specific subtypes of
      Conventional may be needed to express such nuances.  Thus 
      regular bedtime and usual bedtime and normal bedtime all
      have the attribute Conventional.  For activities that occur
      at a particular time of day, day of the week and also recur
      at fixed time intervals, use OccurringAtaFixedTime.
